\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criteria 1\'2C 2\'2C 3\'2C 5\'2C 6\'2C 7\'2C and 8 are in need of improvement. The judgement is mainly based on the fact that the institution has not submitted sufficient or clear information that allows for a proper evaluation. As the evaluator noted\'2C it seems that the focus is on the development of lay counsellors to address the need in this field in the country. However\'2C this aspect is not clarified sufficiently in the design of the programme as the purpose of the qualification is not explicit and therefore the exit level outcomes of this programme are also not clear. For example\'2C it is mentioned that the site is an accredited psychological intern site but there is no indication of how this aspect relates to the qualification or how it relates to the mission and plan of the institution. If the institution envisages that the certificate could be a continuous professional development opportunity for registered counsellors\'2C it should be stated more clearly. In curriculum design it is difficult to follow the module outcomes and the learning and assessment tasks. \line The evaluator found the outline of the certificate comprehensive but questions the amount of specialisations provided. The evaluator felt that the outline provided is more on the level of a registered counsellor \'28NQF 8\'29 than a lay counsellor. The evaluator could also not determine any focus in the list of readings on lay counselling and the course developers do not distinguish in the outline of the practical counselling skills between lay counselling and registered counselling. Again it has to do with the lack of clarity of the purpose of the qualification. \line \line This lack of clarity is also reflected in the marketing material.  The advertising and promotional materials do not contain accurate information. E.g. On the brochure it is stated that  delivery is through face-to face and distance education. However\'2C the application form does not indicate distance learning. Prospective students are not advised on what exactly they will be able to do with this certificate. It is also not clear that the focus of this certificate is on lay counselling. \line Although there is a great need nationally for the training of lay-counsellors and this is adequately highlighted in the application\'2C the documents do not provide sufficient information of how students are admitted or selected into the programme. The admission requirements for the advanced certificate are thus not clear. In the admissions protocol Level 2 it is stated that the academic director should screen the candidates for the BPsych degree programme. This is an advanced certificate not a BPysch degree. Information provided is thus incorrect. \line \line In addition there is a concern of how all the specialisations can be taught adequately with contract staff involved. It is also not clear where the staff are situated \'E2\'80\'93 Cape Town or Johannesburg and how they will be utilized at these campuses. There is\'2C however\'2C an intention to appoint full-time staff. \line \line Given the large number of uncertainties\'2C the Directorate cannot support the recommendation of the evaluator that the programme should be accredited. \line \cell \pard 

